    <h2 style="margin-top:80px;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="content-section">
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h4>What is a Dividend Aristocrat?</h4>
            <p>A Dividend Aristocrat is a company in the S&P 500 index that has increased its dividend payout every year for at least 25 consecutive years. These companies have demonstrated consistent profitability and commitment to returning capital to shareholders through decades of market cycles, recessions, and economic uncertainty.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h4>Which Dividend Aristocrat has the highest yield?</h4>
            <p>The highest yielding Dividend Aristocrat can vary based on market conditions, but typical leaders have yields exceeding 5%. Use our interactive screener above and sort by "Yield (%)" to see the current leaders. Remember that a high yield alone isn't always the best indicator — investors should also consider payout ratio sustainability and earnings growth.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h4>Are Dividend Aristocrats good investments?</h4>
            <p>Dividend Aristocrats have historically performed well with lower volatility compared to the broader market. Their 25+ year track record of dividend increases demonstrates financial discipline and durable competitive advantages. They provide a growing income stream that can help offset inflation. However, past performance doesn't guarantee future results, and some aristocrats trade at premium valuations.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <div class="content-section">
        <p>This study analyzes the S&P 500 Dividend Aristocrats list. Tickers and base classifications were sourced via Wikipedia and cross-referenced. Real-time financial metrics (Current Yield, Payout Ratio, P/E Ratios, Market Cap, Beta) were aggregated using Yahoo Finance APIs. Financial Health Scores are estimated on a 1-10 scale based on basic solvency and liquidity ratios (Current Ratio, Debt-to-Equity).</p>
        <p>Data such as consecutive years of dividend increases relies on publicly available historical data. If unavailable directly, conservative estimates or historical mappings from previous years are used.</p>
    </div>
</div>

